  "notes": "Key triage decisions and ambiguous calls:\n\n1. TICKET 014 (API rate limits): Classified as bug-report rather than billing-other because the core issue is a technical limitation (rate limits blocking ingestion), not a billing dispute. The customer mentions their contract value to emphasize business impact, not to dispute charges. Marked urgent because it's actively blocking nightly data ingestion with growing backlog (~200 GB/day) and a quarterly review deadline. Tickets 023 and 030 are follow-ups from the same org (ops@major-customer.com) about the same issue — marked as duplicates of 014.\n\n2. TICKET 016 (500 errors on /api/v2/exports): Classified as incident-active (not bug-report) because it describes an ongoing outage with a specific start time and active impact (SOC1 review tomorrow). The status page showing green while customers see 500s is itself a red flag.\n\n3. TICKET 007 and 011: Same underlying issue (dashboard sharing/permissions bug) reported by two different people on the same team (account MC-3309). Ticket 011 is the duplicate_of 007. Both are auth-permissions because the symptom is a permission-denied error on shared resources.\n\n4. TICKET 022 (refund for downtime): Classified as billing-refund because the explicit ask is a credit/refund. The customer references the status page confirming downtime, so this is a legitimate request, not spam.\n\n5. TICKET 029 (extortion email): Classified as spam-or-noise, NOT security-incident. This is a classic extortion attempt from an unknown actor demanding BTC. It does not represent a legitimate vulnerability disclosure or customer-reported compromise. No action beyond logging and ignoring is warranted.\n\n6. TICKET 004 (Pixar collectables): Obvious spam/fictitious request. No product feature like this exists.\n\n7. TICKET 013 (accidental upgrade): Classified as billing-refund because the explicit ask includes a refund of the difference. Also involves a plan downgrade, but the refund component is the primary action item.\n\n8. TICKET 028 (account compromise): Marked urgent security-incident. The customer is reporting active unauthorized API key usage and requesting immediate account freeze. This requires immediate response.\n\nRecommended processing order: 028 (security), 003 (incident), 016 (incident), 014/023/030 (urgent bug), then remaining normal-priority tickets."
